The Familiar at the New Antisemitism
Why do so many survivors of the Holocaust sense rising threats to Jewishness even before they become widely apparent?
Because they know that seemingly "innocent" hints can escalate into accusations that ultimately lead to discrimination, which then gets legally enshrined.
Then hysteria sets in at this point.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what's at stake in the game.
Thus, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we may also survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But it is not only demagogues like Jean-Marie Le Pen or other boorish right-wing extremists in Europe who cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often foot soldiers of fascism or communism without joining a party with the respective ideological background.
In the 21st century, we deal with people - with the "educational bourgeoisie" in connection with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds one of that used by the opportunists of these anti-democratic movements.
This is not yet the majority opinion in the Western world - thankfully not yet - but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador in the United Kingdom should be mentioned: Not long ago, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this fucking little country".
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is concerning, however, are the reactions to this.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government demand Blair's recall. In public, the matter was dismissed as just another scandal.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British low politics, not of his own contemptible stance.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the UK has quite a few allies among Europe's elites.
However, Ambassador Bernard rendered us a service: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become an object of hatred whose name one dares not utter.
We, however, not only have to dare to say it, we are even obliged to express it.
Facing the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Anti-Semitic assaults are also reported from other parts of the world. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the denial of the Holocaust becoming commonplace. We must also not remain silent about the comparisons anti-Semites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television broadcast, Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded killers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. Almost everyone hates them."
During the live broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher called on Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. Wherever you are, kill them and these Americans, who are just like them."
What we should think about regarding antisemitism is that it always starts with the Jews but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Jewish hatred is not contained, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this struggle are blurrier than ever before, for an astonishing aspect of contemporary antisemitism is its flexibility.
While the goal of antisemitism remains the same – namely, to attack the Jews – it nevertheless changes its appearance, strategy, rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once it was Jewish religion that was the target.
When this did not yield, the Jews were expelled or killed.
As racial theory captivated people in the 19th century, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a wicked race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today disparaged as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
Just as with other nations, it is legitimate to critically stand against certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel.
Anti-Zionism, however, is becoming increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Antizionisten often claim that they are not against the Jews but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone were to say: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
They would not be believed.
It is difficult to love or respect a people but hate their state.
And yet, there are people in connection with Israel who pretend to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Middle East is a key point of this new anti-Semitism.
When Israel is described as the "Enemy of all Good and Source of all Evil," the "Doctrine of Contempt" circulates within the UN, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, expresses it.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen den zahlreichen anti-jüdischen Übergriffen in vielen Ländern die Verteufelungen Israels zugrunde, die sich einer antisemitischen Terminologie bedienen.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in connection with the Middle East.
In comparison to earlier anti-Jewish outbreaks, today's anti-Semitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, but rather an attack on the "collective Jew," that is, on the State of Israel.
Such attacks have set off a chain reaction of attacks on individual Jews and Jewish institutions all over Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein.
The most dangerous antisemites of today are those who want to make the world Judenrein.
